			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2249">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Stephen Elliott&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href="/article/753">Bamboozled: Dispatches from the Nader Campaign</a>&rdquo; [February 2001] helped fill the gap in mainstream journalism&rsquo;s coverage of Ralph Nader&rsquo;s and the Green Party&rsquo;s role in the last presidential election. Thank you for a welcome glimpse into a small part of history, and for an article so entertainingly written.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Chuck Joy<br>Erie, Pennsylvania</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="2250">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Stephen Elliott&rsquo;s journal entries about campaigning for Ralph Nader shed some light on why Nader&rsquo;s bid was so unsuccessful: sneering condescension and New Age machismo are not the most effective campaign tactics.</p>

<p>As a college-age woman, I can say that, had I been confronted with a &ldquo;short white guy&rdquo; in a janitor&rsquo;s uniform who ogled me (carefully noting whether or not I was wearing a bra), consistently referred to me as a &ldquo;girl,&rdquo; and fed me tired and obvious exaggerations (Bush is a &ldquo;not-so-distant relative of Hitler&rdquo;; Gore a &ldquo;compulsive liar&rdquo;), I might have been a little reluctant to vote for his candidate. Fortunately, I watched Nader on <span class="smallcaps">TV</span> and got a better impression.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Ellen Garrison<br>Brooklyn, New York</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

